    "type": "Question",
    "name": "Question 12 @ 2022/2023",
    "Question": {
      "content": "The potential difference between the terminals of a source when no current flows in an external circuit is called the",
      "type": "OBJ",
      "options": [
        "net voltage",
        "Battery voltage",
        "Electromotive",
        "Equivalent voltage"
      ]
    },
    "Answer": {
      "type": "string",
      "content": "Electromotive"
    },
    "Explanation": {
      "type": "string",
      "content": "<div style='font-family: Arial, sans-serif; line-height: 1.6;'><h3 style='color: #2c3e50;'>Electromotive Force (EMF)</h3><p>The <strong>EMF</strong> of a source is defined as the potential difference across its terminals when <em>no current flows</em> (open circuit). This represents the maximum voltage the source can provide.</p><h4 style='color: #2c3e50; margin-top: 15px;'>Key Characteristics:</h4><ul><li>Measured in <strong>volts (V)</strong></li><li>Accounts for the source's internal energy conversion (e.g., chemical to electrical in batteries)</li><li>Differs from terminal voltage under load due to internal resistance</li></ul><h4 style='color: #2c3e50;'>Why Other Options Are Incorrect:</h4><table style='width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin: 15px 0;'><tr><th style='border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 8px; background: #f2f2f2;'>Option</th><th style='border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 8px; background: #f2f2f2;'>Analysis</th></tr><tr><td style='border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 8px;'>Net voltage</td><td style='border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 8px;'>Not a standard term in circuit theory</td></tr><tr><td style='border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 8px;'>Battery voltage</td><td style='border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 8px;'>Refers to terminal voltage under load</td></tr><tr><td style='border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 8px;'>Equivalent voltage</td><td style='border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 8px;'>Used in circuit reduction, not source characterization</td></tr></table></div>"
    },
    "topic": [
      "Electromotive Force",
      "Electricity & Magnetism",
      "Electric Potential",
      "DC Circuits"
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "Question",
    "name": "Question 24 @ 2022/2023",
    "Question": {
      "content": "A battery of internal resistance 2Ω is connected in series with a resistor of 20 Ω. If the potential difference across the resistor is 6V. Calculate the e.m.f of the battery.",
      "type": "subJective"
    },
    "Answer": {
      "type": "string",
      "content": "6.6V"
    },
    "Explanation": {
      "type": "string",
      "content": "<div style='font-family: Arial, sans-serif; line-height: 1.6;'><h3 style='color: #2c3e50;'>EMF with Internal Resistance</h3><p>Using the circuit relationships:</p><p style='background: #f8f9fa; padding: 10px; border-left: 4px solid #3498db;'><strong>I = V<sub>R</sub>/R = 6V/20Ω = 0.3A</strong><br><strong>EMF = V<sub>R</sub> + Ir = 6V + (0.3A × 2Ω) = <strong>6.6V</strong></strong></p></div>"
    },
    "topic": [
      "DC Circuits",
      "Resistance",
      "Electric Current",
      "Ohm's Law",
      "Electromotive Force",
      "Electric Potential"
    ]
